Rating: 3
I would cut down on the garlic and cook the eggplant about 10 minutes longer than the recipe says. It was a great salad the day of and several days after being made. Everyone I shared it with liked it.

Rating: 4
I absolutely love this recipe! I have never really thought of eggplant as a good food to eat before, but I am addicted to this recipe and make it at least once a week. My husband loves it, too. I make it exactly the same as the recipe... the fresh dill and garlic really make it great.

Rating: 4
This recipe is a keeper! Subsituted balsamic vinegar and used red onions. Sliced the garlic cloves in halves to bring out the garlic flavor. Did not have cherry tomatoes on hand, so diced a couple red vines into chunks and worked out just fine. Needed some salt and pepper. Tastes great at room temperature. A great side dish during your summer grilling. This dish compliments a good bottle of wine!

Rating: 3
Great way to use summer vegetables. Used what was in the garden (zucchini, crook-neck squash, green peppers, red onion, yellow tomatoes) and dried herbs. Very tasty, even the kiddos liked it. Will make again. . .might try fresh rosemary next time.

Rating: 3
I really liked this recipe -- letting the salad sit for a while definitely helped pull it together. It helped that the cherry tomatoes I had were very good. I didn't have enough eggplant, so I roasted some fennel I found in the fridge and threw it in, too. It was a nice variation.

Rating: 3
A little bland but an excellent way to serve eggplant especially to the new eggplant diner.

Rating: 4
Great recipe! Substituted wine vinegar for balsamic and added the juice of half a lemon. Chilled in the refrigerator and served with warmed lavash bread. I would consider adding pinenuts (or finely chopped walnuts for a Gerorgian touch?) for some texture next time.

Rating: 4
Easy, delicious and a big hit with guests when served as an hors d'oeuvre with warm pita triangles.

